EditorData.stateContext: Cazador is lying in his coffin

Text.Value: *The vampire lord lies before you, still as death.*
They will gnaw at their own flesh before long, in an effort to fight off the hunger. It would have been kinder, and less cowardly, to kill them.

EditorData.NodeContext: judgmental - player left thousands of vampire spawn imprisoned for eternity, and Minthara thinks this was cowardly and cruel. She's not sad, more annoyed with what she sees as a poor decision

Text.Value: Kill Cazador.
A merciful end. To lock them away forever would have been an unbearable agony.
So many dead... we'll never wash this blood from our hands.
Perhaps its for the best. Freeing them could have unleashed chaos, and the thought of killing them is more than I could stomach.
I sleep, but cannot rest. I live, but cannot die. I am eternal, and I grieve.
These deathless dreams hold memories of a mortal life once-forgotten. Of the boy I was, the man I became, the monster that will not end.
The spawn have their freedom - but what of the city, what of the lives they take? Gods, I can't imagine...
It's done. Just like that. Gods, help us.
If they be innocent, they deserve life. If they be not - death. This hanging about in between... it is uncommon cruel.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quietly disgruntled with our decision to keep the vampire spawn alive but imprisoned - almost pities them

Text.Value: A herd of vampire spawn, unleashed on the Sword Coast. What could go wrong?
I didn't realise you had such a soft streak. Now it'll cost you. And the city as well, perhaps...

EditorData.NodeContext: Disapproving (but not deeply angry - just thinks it was a bad call)

Text.Value: A cold kind of mercy - but mercy still, I think.
Destroy them with the staff's dark magic.
Leave.
To end so many with only rhyming and words... the sword would have been messy, yes. But cleaner too, thinks Boo.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little shaken by the ritual 'mercy-killing' of thousands of vampire spawn he just witnessed. They were beasts, yes, but even beasts deserve a death in battle.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The prisoners in the cells scream and explode, sending a rain of blood down on us

Text.Value: Snuffed out in an instant, but to whose satisfaction? They will never feed and never be hunted. And never have a chance to hew their own paths.
All those lives, just snuffed out... I hope it was worth it.
Wise choice. Now the streets will be safer and you'll be stronger.
*The great vampire lord looks peaceful, recovering in his coffin. There is no trace of the fury that you fought against.*

EditorData.AnimationTags: Please reuse HUM_M_Rig_CINE_BendForward_Look_02 for player looking into the coffin. Pose of Cazador lying down with the dagger asleep needed. <Gwen Lee>
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: players stand around Cazador's coffin, looking down at the sleeping vampire. His hands are crossed over his chest, and a dagger is held in them

Text.Value: Fly, little vampires! Return to this city, and you will answer to BOO!

EditorData.NodeContext: Minsc is only now realising the gravity of letting them all free - so he leaves them with this parting threat

Text.Value: Entombed forever beneath the city, starving and yet unable to die. True death might have been kinder.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player opens the coffin lid to reveal Cazador lying in his coffin.

Text.Value: Use the staff to set the prisoners free.
Seven thousand vampire spawns, unleashed on the Sword Coast. It'll be a well-dressed flood of mayhem, at least.
*Nothing remains now. Cazador and his machinations are naught but dust.*
Glorious.

EditorData.NodeContext: in awe, having just watched thousands of people die at the player's command. Impressed.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Player snaps the staff over their knee (or other method of destroying the staff)

Text.Value: You did the right thing. All those deaths would have weighed you down.
Consummatum est - ego cecidi.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Player yanks the dagger out and stabs Cazador. Cazador reacts, speaks his final words and die. Dagger falls after he turns to dust? Or it turns to dust too? <Gwen Lee>
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Player takes the ancient dagger that Cazador holds, and plunges it through his heart. He wakes on impact,  looks at the player who killed him. Speaks his final words softly, as he turns to dust.
EditorData.NodeContext: Latin - 'It is finished - I fall.' (kon-soom-AH-toom est - E-go che-CHEE-dee)

Text.Value: All those lives snuffed out, just to grasp some power. That was craven - unnatural.
*The coffin lies silent, containing nothing but dust and memories.*
*The vampire lord is no more, but his legacy remains: seven thousand vampire spawn, including the stolen children of the Gur hunters. What will you do with them all?*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player picks up Cazador's staff, which is lying in the now-otherwise-empty coffin.

Text.Value: Eternal imprisonment. Would have been kinder to just kill them.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Player holds the staff before them with two hands and focuses.

Text.Value: *His dreams have the form of an endless ocean of blood, vast and unknowable.*
I should applaud the liberation of bound creatures. But somehow I sense I will be the one cleaning up this mess.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: We see prison doors swinging open and vampire spawn taking their first tentative steps out of their cells.

Text.Value: Gods, the horror of being forever locked away. The grave would have been a more merciful fate.
Liberating them may be a salve to your conscience, but it is not a kindness. The city's poorer quarters will be their feasthall.
A wise choice. Let nature determine their fates.
*The vampire lord is no more, but his legacy remains. What to do with the thousands of vampire spawn he created?*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player picks up Cazador's staff, which is lying in the now-otherwise-empty coffin.

Text.Value: Explore his thoughts.
Destroy the staff so the vampiric prisoners can never escape.
This doesn't feel right. I don't know what else to do, but still...

EditorData.NodeContext: Uneasy. Torn between a bad choice and a worse choice. Sad because it reminds her of her own situation of being trapped in Hell.

Text.Value: Eternally trapped - a damned existence all its own. Never to be predator, never to be prey.
This may keep the city safe, but to seal all those unfortunates away forever...? Death would have been more merciful.
They have their freedom... but what of the city? Have we just unleashed a plague onto the streets?

Synopsis: Dialog which happens if you defeat Cazador without Astarion and outside the ritual. Ends with a decision whether to free, destroy, or trap the remaining vampire spawn prisoners.
